<P>
BRITISH HOSTAGE DIES IN IRAQ, APPARENTLY FROM HEART ATTACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BAGHDAD 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 57-year-old British man held by Iraq at a strategic site has died in 
captivity, apparently from a heart attack, a British Embassy official said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokesman in London identified the dead man as Donald Major. 
</P>
<P>
His hometown was not immediately known. The embassy official said Major died 
Tuesday at the undisclosed strategic site where he was being held hostage. 
</P>
<P>
"This confirms the underlying need for Iraq to respond to our appeals for the 
immediate release of all hostages," said the Foreign Office spokesman, who 
spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
An unidentified colleague released by Iraq informed the embassy of the death 
and said the man appeared to die of a heart attack, said the embassy official, 
who also spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
The official said the man was the first British hostage known to have died in 
captivity. Three other Britons died of natural causes while in hiding in Kuwait 
and two were killed in a car accident in October while trying to drive from 
Kuwait to the Iraq port of Basra. 
</P>
